# Effective Java Checklist

Apply these on every Java change. Prefer compile-time safety over runtime checks.

## Creating & Destroying Objects

- Prefer static factory methods over public constructors when names add clarity (`JSONata.jsonata(...)`).
- Enforce singletons with `enum` or private constructor + static accessor — not mutable static fields.
- Eliminate obsolete object references (clear collections, avoid unintentional leaks in long-lived parsers).
- Avoid creating unnecessary objects in hot paths (reuse immutable instances, `String` constants).

## Common Methods

- Obey `equals`/`hashCode` contract together; use `Objects.equals` / `Objects.hash`.
- Always override `toString` on value types and exceptions meant for debugging.
- Override `clone` carefully or avoid it; prefer copy constructors/factories.

## Classes & Interfaces

- Minimize accessibility — prefer package-private or `private` until API need is proven.
- Favor immutability: `final` fields, no setters, defensive copies on construction.
- Prefer interfaces over abstract classes for type definitions (`Mapping`, `Data`).
- Design interfaces for evolution; use default methods sparingly and document invariants.

## Generics & Types

- Eliminate raw types; never suppress unchecked warnings without justification.
- Prefer bounded wildcards (`? extends T`, `? super T`) on public API collections.
- Use `@SuppressWarnings("unchecked")` only on the smallest scope with a comment why.

## Enums & Annotations

- Use enums for fixed constant sets with behavior (operators, built-in identifiers).
- Use `@Override` on every override; use `@FunctionalInterface` on single-method interfaces.

## Methods

- Check parameters for null/invalid state at entry; throw `NullPointerException` or `IllegalArgumentException` with message.
- Make defensive copies when exposing mutable internals.
- Return empty collections (`List.of()`, `Collections.emptyList()`) instead of `null`.
- Use `Optional` only as a return type for absent values — never fields or parameters.

## General Programming

- Prefer primitives where null is impossible; use boxed types only in generics/collections.
- Know and use the standard library (`Objects`, `List.of`, `Stream`, `Pattern`, `Math`).
- Avoid float/double for monetary or exact numeric semantics when precision matters.

## Imports

- Import only classes that are used — remove unused imports before finishing a change.
- Every referenced type must have an explicit `import` at the top of the file.
- Never use fully qualified class names in method bodies, fields, or signatures (e.g. avoid `java.util.List`, `dev.vepo.jsonata.exception.JSONataException` inline).
- The only exception is a **name collision**: when two types share the same simple name, import one and use the fully qualified name for the other.
- Do not use wildcard imports (`import java.util.*;`) — import each type explicitly.

## Exceptions

- Use checked exceptions only when callers can recover; prefer unchecked for programming errors.
- Wrap low-level exceptions with domain context (`JSONataException`) preserving cause.
- Never swallow exceptions; never use exceptions for ordinary control flow.

## Concurrency & Modules

- Document thread-safety on public types. Prefer immutable, stateless evaluators.
- Respect `module-info.java` exports/opens; do not break module boundaries.

## Serialization

- Avoid Java serialization for domain types; use JSON via existing Jackson adapters when persistence is needed.

## Project-Specific

- Java 21 features allowed: `var`, records (for immutable DTOs), pattern matching where it clarifies code.
- Run `mvn test` before finishing; keep SonarCloud warnings in mind (complexity, duplication).
